Several countries, organizations, and companies are working to improve the quality of life by addressing social and climate issues. Despite considerable efforts and advances in addressing these issues, several challenges appear to be unattainable by 2030 in many developing countries [1]. To expedite the attainment of SDGs (Box 1
                     ), innovative approaches are required. Disease monitoring and biomarker detection (biodetection) are serious challenges in developing countries [2]. Current biodetection strategies have shown some limitations that potentially impact on the achievement of SDGs (Box 2
                     ). However, emerging tools such as microfluidic electrochemical biosensors exhibit some specific features that make them suitable for advancing these goals [3].
